  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "It's important to emphasize, however, that computational models often include several additional parameters.",
    "Aside from the precision-weighting of sensory signals, individuals can also have differences in (for example) prior beliefs about what they will perceive (assumed in any Bayesian model of perception; e.g., predictive coding [62]), and differences in how quickly they update those prior beliefs over repeated observations (i.e., \"learning rate\"; i.e., which can be dependent upon the relative precisions of sensory signals and prior beliefs).",
    "Formal computational models are often necessary to distinguish which parameters show differences between individuals and best explain differences in perception.",
    "Thus, there are multiple computational mechanisms that could account for individual differences in interoception in clinical populations.",
    "One major goal in computational psychiatry is to \"computationally phenotype\" patients by identifying which sets of a parameter values best account for their neural and behavioral responses (including self-reported perceptual experience) and use this information to guide treatment [20, 22, 25]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Aside from the precision-weighting of sensory signals, individuals can also have differences in (for example) prior beliefs about what they will perceive (assumed in any Bayesian model of perception; e.g., predictive coding [62]), and differences in how quickly they update those prior beliefs over repeated observations (i.e., \"learning rate\"; i.e., which can be dependent upon the relative precisions of sensory signals and prior beliefs).",
    "One major goal in computational psychiatry is to \"computationally phenotype\" patients by identifying which sets of a parameter values best account for their neural and behavioral responses (including self-reported perceptual experience) and use this information to guide treatment [20, 22, 25]."
